VII, 11. ’ The ethical doctrines os the Stoics have thus an essentially religious character, though not a theological one; the theological portion is limited to a very few simple propositione, which would rather recommend than injure them in the eyes of many. Not to enter more fully into the subject a single point may be mentioned, which has been noticed by Simplicius in his commentary to Epictetus, Euchir, p. 8. He says: καὶ τοῦτο δ’ dv τις τῶν λθγωνποθτων θαυμάσειεν, ὃτι τοὺς πειθομένους καὶ ἐργαζομένους τὰ λογό- greve μακαρίους ἀποτελοῦσι καὶ εὐδαίμονος, οὐδὲν δεηθέντες τὰς μετὰ θάνατον τῆς ὁρετῆς ιἰμοιβὰς ἐπαγγέλλεσθαι, κᾶν πάντως ἀκολουθῶσιν καὶ οὗτοι. And so it really is; Epictetus never refers to a reward to be expected after death. Although the Stoics never denied the continuing existence of the seul after death, many of them having expressly professed their belief in it,
